00:52:06.291 --> 00:52:08.130
Not built in.

00:52:08.130 --> 00:52:08.971
Not built in.

00:52:08.971 --> 00:52:11.211
Okay, great.

00:52:11.211 --> 00:52:12.051
Let's see.

00:52:13.211 --> 00:52:14.810
We had another question that was,

00:52:14.810 --> 00:52:18.450
can we use parallel detect cores

00:52:18.450 --> 00:52:20.771
to see how many daemons we can use?

00:52:20.771 --> 00:52:21.771
I really like this question

00:52:21.771 --> 00:52:24.971
because I don't know how many daemons I would have access to.

00:52:24.971 --> 00:52:26.930
And that's a great question.

00:52:26.930 --> 00:52:30.091
And like Mirai by design forces you

00:52:30.091 --> 00:52:32.411
to actually specify the number you want.

00:52:32.411 --> 00:52:35.250
So that can be, you know, that can be 14,

00:52:35.250 --> 00:52:39.370
which is sort of the number of cores I have on my laptop.

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:42.611
So you can use something like parallel,

00:52:42.611 --> 00:52:44.810
sorry, parallel detect cores or whatever.

00:52:46.370 --> 00:52:47.211
Bam.

00:52:47.211 --> 00:52:48.810
But, you know, you can easily be on a server

00:52:48.810 --> 00:52:51.171
with, you know, 256 cores or something.

00:52:51.171 --> 00:52:54.211
And like, sometimes you don't want to use all your cores

00:52:54.211 --> 00:52:56.411
because you might be running something else, right?

00:52:56.411 --> 00:52:58.611
So like, it never has that context,

00:52:58.611 --> 00:53:03.611
you running a automatic function.

00:53:04.171 --> 00:53:07.370
The other reason is this,

00:53:07.370 --> 00:53:10.450
like you might want to be using your cores

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:15.450
if what you're doing is compute intensive, right?

00:53:15.890 --> 00:53:18.450
You want to sort of utilize all your cores.

00:53:18.450 --> 00:53:19.330
Fine.

00:53:19.330 --> 00:53:21.930
But instead, if what you're doing

00:53:21.930 --> 00:53:25.651
is actually waiting on IO,

00:53:25.651 --> 00:53:30.651
so this is like, if you're requesting like a download, right?

00:53:30.651 --> 00:53:33.531
That is actually not taking all your computation power.

00:53:33.531 --> 00:53:34.890
So for those kinds of tasks,

00:53:34.890 --> 00:53:36.611
you might actually want to use more

00:53:36.611 --> 00:53:38.490
than the number of cores you have.

00:53:38.490 --> 00:53:40.690
So you might want to use like 28,

00:53:40.690 --> 00:53:44.890
like if all you're doing is like querying some remote API.

00:53:44.890 --> 00:53:47.411
So that's also another reason why like,

00:53:47.411 --> 00:53:49.851
I don't sort of try and assume

00:53:49.851 --> 00:53:51.531
like the number that people want.

00:53:52.570 --> 00:53:53.851
And yeah.

