00:54:02.291 --> 00:54:04.851
would parallel processing be more useful

00:54:04.851 --> 00:54:07.010
than async processing, do you think?

00:54:09.250 --> 00:54:10.091
Yes.

00:54:11.690 --> 00:54:14.611
And Mirai actually powers a lot of things

00:54:14.611 --> 00:54:15.851
sort of under the hood, right?

00:54:15.851 --> 00:54:18.851
So if you're using parallel per,

00:54:19.930 --> 00:54:22.851
that uses Mirai, so you set daemons,

00:54:22.851 --> 00:54:25.611
but you use the normal per syntax,

00:54:25.611 --> 00:54:27.531
and that is just parallel.

00:54:27.531 --> 00:54:28.731
It's not async.

00:54:28.731 --> 00:54:32.250
Where async really sort of comes into its own

00:54:32.250 --> 00:54:36.171
is if you're using Mirai with Shiny,

00:54:36.171 --> 00:54:39.411
or you're using Mirai with something like Plumber 2.

00:54:39.411 --> 00:54:42.890
So again, Mirai powers Plumber 2 under the hood.

00:54:42.890 --> 00:54:45.611
So if you use an async function in Plumber 2,

00:54:45.611 --> 00:54:47.531
that implicitly uses Mirai.

